ce:section.ce:para:
As WCA measurements in Fig. 4
                            show, the EP-PDMS and the related nanocomposite samples have hydrophobic nature with WCA > 120° before immersion in the electrolyte. In the case of samples not immersed in the solution, the EP-PDMS has higher WCA than the prepared nanocomposite coatings. The higher WCA of the EP-PDMS is assigned to the high tendency of h-PDMS for migration to the top surface of the EP coating to form Si-CH3 groups on the surface, while the nanofillers inhibit the h-PDMS migration through preparing high cross-linked structure [54–56]. Besides, the WCA on all the samples decreases by increasing the time of immersion to 20 days, which is still in the hydrophobic range. The WCA results are consistent with the surface roughness data derived from the LSCM (Fig. 5
                           ). The results of root mean square surface roughness (Sq) indicate that the EP-PDMS coating has the highest Sq value, which decreases either by prolonging the time of immersion or loading nanofillers in its matrix. However, both chemical and topological parameters could control the surface properties of the nanocomposite samples [57].
